{
  "doc_id": "42376",
  "text": "We have focused on ribosome-associated chaperone, the trigger factor (Tig, a functional homologue of the eukaryotic RAC/NAC) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] as well as chaperonin GroEL/ES and chaperone DnaK/ DnaJ complexes (homologues of eukaryotic Hsp60/Hsp10 and Hsp70/Hsp40 complexes, respectively). Tig acts during the nascent polypeptide synthesis, to prevent premature folding, i.e., misfolding, of proteins exiting the ribosomal tunnel. After their release from the Tig, some proteins fold without any further assistance but, depending on their size and domain complexity, populations of ''client'' proteins are delivered either to the GroEL/ ES or to the DnaK/DnaJ complex [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
